{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f709ea2a-311d-4ac8-a6eb-3234a93046cd","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Action | Events fired |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created` → `Activated` |\n| User switches away | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` |\n| User returns | `Resumed` → `Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` → `Destroying` |\n\n> **Note:** `Backgrounding` is iOS/Mac Catalyst only — use it to save state before the OS may terminate the app. On Android/Windows it won't fire.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4a71f0ce-7ab1-40d8-b21a-243327c04c34","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for debugging/logging purposes. This is a general programming knowledge question, so I can answer it directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":425,"requestId":"1435:1BD824:A5B051:BBDAD5:6A03CCBA"},"id":"1d71d075-c782-4283-947f-899db80fe3fd","timestamp":"2026-05-13T00:58:43.272Z","parentId":"df891877-e3c0-41b6-8381-f20507d77a06"}
